''See also [[stød]]''
==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*stōdō-'', from Indo-European ''*sta-, *stə-'' ‘stand, set’.  Cognate with Old High German [[stuot]] (German [[Stute]] ‘mare’), Old Norse [[stoð|stóð]] (Swedish [[sto]] ‘mare’).  The IE root is also the source of Old Church Slavonic [[штадо]] (Russian [[штадо]] ‘herd’), Lithuanian [[stodas]] ‘seedling’, as well as the Germanic verbs for ‘stand’ (OE [[standan]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /sto:d/

===Noun===
'''stōd'''
# an enclosure for breeding horses
# a [[horse]] or [[horses]] used for breeding

===See also===
'''stōd''' ''verb form''
* first- or third-person singular preterite of [[standan]]

